Text: And another week is behind us .
When I look back, I have the impression that we've done so little, and there is so much to do before us.
And then I open the notes from our meetings and google drive, and suddenly it turns out that we did quite well, which does not change the fact that it is still far away.
I do not write about time, because it shrinks mercilessly, but the number of tasks yet to be done.
This week, we finally met the whole group in person - it was easier to communicate and determine what we are going to do next and divide the tasks.

We summarized our presentation and concluded that we prepared it in terms of substance, but technically (listing the roles, tasks, and systems that we will use), and in terms of appearance, our presentation left much to desire.
The next presentation is ahead of us in two weeks, we are assuming improvement, but how far-reaching - nobody knows it : ).
The plan for this week was: .
1/ Meeting with a focus group of teenagers so that we can find out what young people expect and what their ideas for riding a simulator are and what they would like to see.
We were able to organize a meeting with a group of 5 teenagers interested and willing to answer questions (prepared in advance by us).
2/ Meeting/zoom with Tony Savarimuth, which took place on Wednesday, and we received some useful tips, but I do not know if we can introduce them to our project right now.

3/Starting coding, embracing work with GitHub in the group, and finding tools/program/programming language in which we will create our visualization - fortunately, we were able to implement the above.
I am definitely not at the stage of excitement.
For me, it's currently a stage of frustration.
I'm not able to code the visualizations with RShiny at the moment.

Although I prepared the low fidelity project of the last screen in the PowerPoint, I am far from satisfied because I don't know how to translate it into coding - coding is not my strong point in this case.
The comforting fact is that Koko focused on preparing coding with map and CSV files that we received from the client this week, and the first effects are visible.
I took my first steps with R and CSV files, thanks to Tzu-Rara, but it's still a bit of dark magic.
Coding appeals to me as I see the immediate result, i. e. , graphics. In-class with COMP160, the graphic/visible part was the most pleasant and satisfying for me.
It is similar to INFO201 - I coded massive amounts of diagrams there, and the effect was immediately visible.
Yes .this item also spends my sleep from my eyesâ€”the three-hour exam on June 11 just before our final presentation.
And I still don't know what this exam should look like online.
There is a chance that something will explain in the coming week.

Sometimes it is impossible to do everything at once, and I have to repeat it to myself regularly that you need to do step by step or baby steps, such as watch the training from RShiny from beginning to end : ).
Roro, absolutely not in our group, devoted his time to us and explained what RShiny is all about and how to connect with our files or other languages.
He did it noticeably and transparently.
It does not change the fact that I have a long way to go in programming in this language.
Goals for the next week are: .
1/ 2nd meeting with a focus group - to receive feedback on the part of our project - visualization of the last screen.
2/ Coding, coding, and coding again.
3/ Start preparing the presentation.
4/ Preparing for the exam from INFO201.
I also know that coming week we need to relieve Kiki, who is invaluable in matters of formal, linguistic, and purely human relationships, because she expects an exam on June 4. .
Thank you, Teacher1, for sharing your experience with us.
It is beneficial at this stage of our course.
Overall
